column1: # text = 250 g uncooked pasta of your choice
# text = 250 g pancetta, cut into small sticks
# text = 500 g fresh asparagus ends trimmed and cut into 2-inch pieces
# text = Saute pancetta in a large pan over medium-high heat, stirring occasionally, until crispy.
# text = Remove pancetta with a slotted spoon and set aside.
# text = Add asparagus to the pan and saute in the pancetta grease for about 5-6 minutes, stirring occasionally, until almost cooked.
# text = Slowly add the white wine to deglaze the pan.
# text = Continue cooking for 5 minutes or until the wine has reduced by about half.
# text = Cook the pasta in a large pot according to package instructions.
# text = Drain, but reserve 1/4 cup of the pasta water for later (if needed).
# text = Add the pasta, pancetta and 1/4 cup Parmesan cheese to the saute pan with asparagus, and toss until combined.
# text = Sprinkle pasta with the remaining Parmesan cheese and serve immediately.
# text = 2 zucchinis, sliced in small rounds
# text = 1 squash, sliced in small rounds
# text = In a heavy cast enamel oval gratin dish, smear the butter all over the bottom and sides.
# text = Arrange the slices of zucchini and squash, alternating them.
# text = Leave some open space in the middle.
# text = Place the cut tomatoes in the middle of the dish.
# text = In a small skillet with 1 teaspoon of olive oil, saute the onion over medium heat until translucent.
# text = Add some fresh thyme while cooking and season with salt and pepper.
# text = When done, 5 to 8 minutes, gently sprinkle them over the zucchini, squash and tomatoes.
# text = Season with salt and pepper, fresh thyme and a generous amount of olive oil.
# text = Place in the preheated oven and cook for 15 to 20 minutes.
# text = Serve hot or at room temperature.
# text = cream 2 tablespoons butter, beat in eggs and salt.
# text = Gradually beat in flour and riced potatoes.
# text = Dough should be stiff to knead thoroughly.
# text = On floured board roll out dough to 1/4-inch thickness, then cut 3-inch squares.
# text = Lay 1 plum on each square, sprinkle with little cinnamon sugar and fold edges over plum.
# text = Shape with hands into a ball.
# text = The wall of dough should be very thin.
# text = Drop dumplings into boiling salted water, cover and simmer for about 15 minutes.
# text = Brown bread crumbs in 1/3 cup hot butter.
# text = Roll dumplings in buttered bread crumbs, sprinkle with cinnamon sugar.
# text = 1/2 cup freshly squeezed orange juice
# text = 1/4 cup red wine, I used Pinot Noir
# text = 1 12 oz. package of fresh cranberries
# text = Place hibiscus leaves on a piece of cheesecloth and tie into a tight bundle.
# text = In a medium saucepan combine orange juice, red wine, water and brown sugar.
# text = Bring to a boil over medium high heat.
# text = Add hibiscus clove bundle to the liquid and boil for two minutes.
# text = Stir orange zest into mixture and add cranberries.
# text = Bring mixture back to a boil.
# text = Reduce heat to low, cover and simmer for 8 minutes until the liquid reduces.
# text = Pour cranberry sauce into a mason jar and let cool uncovered.
# text = Store in the fridge for up to a week before Thanksgiving.
# text = 3 cups of Gold Medal flour to roll very thin
# text = Mix molasses, sugar, ginger and butter
# text = Stir over the fire until the butter is melted, then stir in quickly flour in which has been sifted the pulverized soda.
# text = Knead the dough until it becomes smooth and set on ice, over night if possible.
# text = Roll as thin as pasteboard and bake in a quick oven.
